<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
 <subsection xml:id="subsec-circumference-of-a-circle">
      <title>circumference of a circle</title>
   <activity>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Round we go!
      </p>
      <p>
        Think of a hula hoop. The circumference is the length of the edge of a hula hoop if you could cut it and stretch it into a straight line. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>
          \textbf{materials needed:} 3 circular objects (cups, lids, tins, etc.), String or flexible measuring tape, Ruler, Calculator, Worksheet or recording sheet
        </m>
      </p>
      <p>
        How many times do you think the diameter of a circle fits around its edge?
      </p>
      <p>
        1. Gather your materials and measure and record:
      </p>
      <p>
         (a) he diameter of each circular object using a flexible ruler or a string. Record the measurements in your work sheet,
      </p>
      <p>
        (b) Measure the string with a ruler.
      </p>
      <p>
        2.  Calculate (Discover the Pattern)
      </p>
      <p>
        (a) Divide: <m>
          \text{Circumference} \div \text{Diameter}
        </m>
        (b) Notice that the ratio is close to 3.14 which is the value of <m>\pi</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        (c) Now that they’ve discovered the pattern, calculate the circumference of each circle using the formula: <m>
          \text{Circumference} = \pi \times \text{Diameter}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>\pi = \frac{C}{d}</m> , then <m> C = \pi \times d</m>. 
          <md>
            <mrow>  C =\amp \pi d </mrow>
          </md>
      </p>
      <p><m>\textbf {Study Questions}</m></p>
      <p>
        1. Why do you think the ratio is the same for all circles?
      </p>
      <p>
        2. How does this help us in real-life situations?
      </p>
      <p>
        3. Draw circles with a compass, measure radii, and use C=2πrC=2πr to calculate the perimeter.
      </p>

    </statement>
   
   </activity>
   
    <p>In this section, you will learn about the circumference of a circle.</p>
    <p>In the previous section, you learned about the diameter and radius of a circle. The diameter is the distance across the circle through its center, while the radius is half of the diameter.</p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p> Circumference = <m>\pi d \text{ where,} \pi =\frac{22}{7} or 3.14</m>  or <m>2 \pi r</m>. <m>d</m>  is the diameter and <m>r</m> is the radius.</p>
       
         <p>
          Find the circumference of the following circle given the radius <m>r = 56 \text{ cm }</m>. Use <m>\pi = \frac {22}{7}.</m>
         </p>
          <image>
          <latex-image label = "circle">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \fill[pink] (0,0) circle (3cm);
            
             % Draw the radius line
             \draw[thick, -&gt;] (0,0) -- (3,0) node[midway, above] {\large $r = 56 cm$};
            
             % Draw the center point
             \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
          </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> \text {Circumference } = \amp \pi d + d</mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp \frac {22}{7} \times 112 \text{ cm }  </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp \frac {2464}{7} \text{ cm }  </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp 352 \text{ cm } </mrow>
              </md>
                            OR
              <md>
               <mrow> \text {Circumference } = \amp 2 \pi \text { r } </mrow>
               <mrow> \amp </mrow>
               <mrow>  = \amp \frac {22}{7} \times 56 \text{ cm } </mrow>
               <mrow>  = \amp \frac {44 \times 56}{7} \text{ cm }  </mrow>
               <mrow>  = \amp  \frac {2464}{7} \text{ cm } + 112 \text { cm }</mrow>
               <mrow> = \amp 352 \text{ cm }</mrow>
              </md>              
            </p>
          </solution>
          </example>
    <p>In the example above, you can see that the circumference of a circle is the distance around it. It is like the perimeter of a polygon, but for circles.</p> 
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the circumference of the following circles. Use <m>\pi = \frac {22}{7}.</m>
        </p>
        <sidebyside>
          <image>
          <latex-image label = "circle-1">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \fill[pink] (0,0) circle (2cm);
            
             % Draw the radius line
             \draw[thick, -&gt;] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, above] {\large $r = 28 cm$};
            
             % Draw the center point
             \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
          </image> 
          
          <image>
          <latex-image label ="radi">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \fill[pink] (0,0) circle (2cm);
            
             % Draw the radius line
             \draw[thick, &lt;-&gt;] (-2,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, below] {\large $d= 35 cm$ };
            
             % Draw the center point
             \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
            \end{tikzpicture}  
          </latex-image>
          </image>
         </sidebyside>   
        </statement>
        
    <p>
      <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
     </p>
     <p>The circumference of a circle is the distance around it. It is like the perimeter of a polygon, but for circles.</p>
    <p>To find the circumference, you can use the formula: <m>\text{Circumference} = \pi d</m> or <m>2 \pi r</m>, where <m>d</m> is the diameter and <m>r</m> is the radius.</p>
    
      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The radius of a flower garden is <m>6</m>m. What length of barbed wire can fence the garden using five strands of the barbed wire? <m>(\text{use} \pi = 3.142)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
           <p>
              <md> 
               <mrow>\text{ Circumference is } 2 \pi r= \amp 2 \times \frac {22}{7} \times 3.142 \times 6 \text {m}</mrow> 
               <mrow> = \amp 37.704 \text{m} </mrow> 
               <mrow> \text { Total length of barbed wire } = \amp 37.704 \text{ m} \times 5</mrow> 
               <mrow> = \amp 188.52 \text{m} </mrow>
              </md>
              md
           </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
    <extendedactivity>
    <p>Note the difference between the formulas for calculating the circumfrence of a circle and a semicircle.</p>
    <p>Share with your friends and classmates.</p>
    </extendedactivity>
    <example>
     <statement>
       <p>
            Find the perimeter of the figure below.
          </p>
        <image>
          <latex-image label = "circle-2">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \fill[pink] (-2,0) arc[start angle=180, end angle=360, radius=2cm] -- (0,0) -- cycle;
              % Draw the radius and label it 'r'
              \draw[thick, -&gt;] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, above] {\large $r = 21 cm$};
              % Draw the center point
              \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
          </image>
     </statement>
      <solution>
       <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> \text{ Circumference } = \amp \frac {1}{2} \pi d + d</mrow>
          <mrow>  d =\amp 2 \text{ r } </mrow>
          <mrow>  d =\amp 42 \text{ cm } </mrow>
          <mrow>  = \amp \frac {1}{2} \times \frac {22}{7} \times 42 \text{ cm } + 42 \text{ cm }   </mrow>
          <mrow>  = \amp \frac {924}{14} \text{ cm } + 42 \text{ cm }   </mrow>
          <mrow>  = \amp ( 66 +42 )\text{ cm }  </mrow>
          <mrow>  = \amp 108 \text{ cm }  </mrow>
        </md>
       </p>
                         <p>OR</p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \text { Circumference } = \amp \pi r + 2r</mrow>
            <mrow>  2 \text{r} =\amp 42 \text{ cm } </mrow>
            <mrow>  = \amp \times \frac {22}{7} \times 21 \text{ cm } + 2(21) \text{ cm }   </mrow>
            <mrow>  = \amp \frac {462}{7} \text{ cm } + 42 \text{ cm }   </mrow>
            <mrow>  = \amp ( 66 + 42 )\text{ cm }  </mrow>
            <mrow>  = \amp 108 \text{ cm }  </mrow>
          </md>
       </p>      
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
     <p>The following circles show the position of hand minutes wall with their respective radii. Calculate the distance covered by each tip.   </p>
     <statement>
       <sidebyside>
         <image>
           <latex-image label = "circle-full">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \fill[blue] (-2,0) arc[start angle=180, end angle=360, radius=2cm] -- (0,0) -- cycle;
              % Draw the radius and label it 'r'
              \draw[thick, -&gt;] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, above] {\large $r = 56.7 cm$};
              % Draw the center point
              \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
              \node at (0,1.5){\textbf{(a)}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
           </latex-image>
          </image>
          <image>
           <latex-image label = "three-quarter-circle">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              % Draw a 3/4 (270-degree) filled green circle
              \fill[green] (0,0) -- (2,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=270, radius=2cm] -- cycle;
              
              % Draw the outline of the 3/4 circle
              \draw[thick] (2,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=270, radius=2cm] -- (0,0) -- cycle;
              
              % Indicate the radius with a label 'r'
              \draw[thick, -&gt;] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway, above] {\large $ r = 7 cm$};
              % Draw the center point
              \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
              \node at (0,1.5){\textbf{(b)}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
           </latex-image>
          </image>
          <image>
           <latex-image label = "quarter-circle">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \fill[pink] (-2,0) arc[start angle=180, end angle=270, radius=2cm] -- (0,0) -- cycle;
              % Draw the radius and label it 'r'
              \draw[thick, -&gt;] (0,0) -- (-2,0) node[midway, above] {\large $r = 21$};
              % Draw the center point
              \fill (0,0) circle (2pt);
              \node at (0,1.5){\textbf{(c)}};
            \end{tikzpicture}
           </latex-image>
          </image>
       </sidebyside>
    </statement>
     <solution>
      <statement>
       <p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
             <p>
              <md>
                <mrow> \text { Circumference } = \amp \pi r + 2r</mrow>
                <mrow>  2 \text{r} =\amp 56.7 \text{ cm }  \times 2 = 113.4 \text{ cm } </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp \times 3.14 \times 56.7 \text{ cm } + 113.4 \text{ cm }  </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp 178.038 \text{ cm } + 113.4 \text{ cm } </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp ( 66 + 42 )\text{ cm }  </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp 291.438 \text{ cm }  </mrow>
              </md>
            </p> 
          </li>
                <li>
                <p>
                  <md>
                    <mrow> \text{ Circumference } = \amp \frac {3}{4} \times 2\pi r + 2 \text {r}</mrow>
                    <mrow>  2 \text{ r }  =\amp 2 \times 7 \text { cm } = 14 \text { cm } </mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp \frac {3}{4} \times \frac {22}{7} \times 14 \text { cm } + 14 \text{ cm }   </mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp \frac {924}{28} \text { cm } + 14 \text{ cm }   </mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp ( 33 + 14 )\text { cm }  </mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp 47 \text{ cm }  </mrow>
                 </md>
               </p> 
          </li>
          <li> 
            <p >
              <md>
                <mrow> \text{ Circumference } = \amp \frac {1}{4} \times 2\pi r + 2 \text {r}</mrow>
                <mrow>  2 \text{ r }  =\amp 2 \times 35 \text { cm } = 70 \text { cm } </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp \frac {1}{4} \times \frac {22}{7} \times 70 \text { cm } + 70 \text{ cm }   </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp \frac {308}{28} \text { cm } + 14 \text{ cm }   </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp ( 110 + 70 )\text { cm }  </mrow>
                <mrow>  = \amp 180 \text{ cm }  </mrow>
              </md>
           </p>  
         </li>   
         </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
     </solution>
    </example>


    
  </subsection>
  